To set up a search UI for a React storefront, you can use **Algolia's React InstantSearch library**. This library provides a set of pre-built UI components that you can use to build a complete search experience, from the search box to the results display and filtering.

### Getting Started with React InstantSearch

The core of the integration involves installing the necessary packages, connecting to your Algolia index, and adding the desired search components to your application. The primary library for this is `react-instantsearch-hooks-web`.

### Step-by-Step Setup

Here is a basic outline of the steps to integrate Algolia search into your React application ([details and examples](https://www.algolia.com/doc/guides/building-search-ui/getting-started/react/)).

**1. Install Dependencies**
First, add the Algolia search client and the React InstantSearch library to your project.

```bash
npm install algoliasearch react-instantsearch-hooks-web
```
or
```bash
yarn add algoliasearch react-instantsearch-hooks-web
```

**2. Initialize the Search Client**
You'll need your **Application ID** and **Search-Only API Key** from your Algolia dashboard to initialize the search client. It's best practice to store these in environment variables.

```javascript
import algoliasearch from 'algoliasearch/lite';

const searchClient = algoliasearch(
  'YOUR_APPLICATION_ID',
  'YOUR_SEARCH_ONLY_API_KEY'
);
```

**3. Implement the Search UI**
Wrap your search components with the `<InstantSearch>` provider. This provider connects your UI to your Algolia index.

Key components include:
*   **`<InstantSearch>`**: The main component that requires the `searchClient` and the `indexName`.
*   **`<SearchBox>`**: The input field for users to type their queries.
*   **`<Hits>`**: The component that receives and displays your search results.
*   **`<RefinementList>`**: A widget to filter results based on a specific attribute (facet).
*   **`<Configure>`**: A component to set search parameters like `hitsPerPage`.

Here is a basic implementation:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import {
  InstantSearch,
  SearchBox,
  Hits,
  Configure,
  RefinementList
} from 'react-instantsearch-hooks-web';
import algoliasearch from 'algoliasearch/lite';

const searchClient = algoliasearch('YOUR_APP_ID', 'YOUR_SEARCH_ONLY_API_KEY');

// Component to define how each result (hit) is displayed
function Hit({ hit }) {
  return (
    <article>
      <h1>{hit.name}</h1>
      <p>{hit.description}</p>
    </article>
  );
}

function App() {
  return (
    <InstantSearch searchClient={searchClient} indexName="your_index_name">
      <Configure hitsPerPage={8} />
      <div className="search-container">
        <div className="left-panel">
          {/* Facet for filtering by brand */}
          <RefinementList attribute="brand" />
        </div>
        <div className="right-panel">
          <SearchBox />
          <Hits hitComponent={Hit} />
        </div>
      </div>
    </InstantSearch>
  );
}

export default App;
```

### Customization
Once you have the basic setup, you can customize the look and feel of any component or even create your own custom widgets to tailor the experience to your storefront's needs ([customization guide](https://www.algolia.com/doc/guides/building-search-ui/widgets/customize-an-existing-widget/react/)).

For more support or info, please feel free to browse our [support articles](https://support.algolia.com/hc/en-us/search) or [docs](https://www.algolia.com/doc). If you still need help, [submit a ticket](https://support.algolia.com/hc/en-us/requests/new) for customer support.
